NowThis Impact spoke to the organization’s CEO, Daniel Forkkio, at the Elevate Prize Foundation’s Make Good Famous Summit about why telling untold stories through film is so powerful.

Check out some of their films at representjustice.org.

title: COVID Origins Controversy Sparks Walkout During NIH Event
description:
About 27 minutes into his speech, as director Dr. Jay Bhattacharya discussed the possibility that NIH-sponsored research contributed to the virus’s origins, dozens of NIH staff — including postdoctoral researchers and union members — walked out in protest.

Prior to the COVID pandemic, the NIH provided funding through grants to EcoHealth Alliance, which in turn collaborated with the Wuhan Institute of Virology to study bat coronaviruses. However, both the NIH and independent investigations have stated that the viruses studied under these grants were genetically distant from SARS-CoV-2 and could not have caused COVID.

title: Aja Speaks Out After Passport Misgendering Incident
description:
Aja the Queen posted on social media that, despite having all the correct documentation, she was still issued a passport with the gender marker ‘M’ to indicate male. ‘This isn’t a clerical error. This is a federal fumble with my life in the crosshairs,’ the star wrote.

The Trump administration decided in January that gender markers on passports must match what individuals were assigned at birth — even if they’ve legally updated other important documents. Aja is just the latest celebrity to be misgendered because of this policy. In February, Hunter Schafer also received a new passport with the incorrect information.

Elon Musk spent over $250M supporting Donald Trump’s 2024 presidential campaign and more than $21M backing conservative Brad Schimel in the 2025 Wisconsin Supreme Court race — aiming to shift the court’s balance.

Despite these record-breaking donations, the Trump administration failed to deliver Musk’s desired reforms, and Schimel lost decisively to liberal Judge Susan Crawford, preserving the court’s liberal majority.

title: The U.S. Just Got a Financial Red Flag. Expect the Ripple Effect
description:
The Trump administration isn’t worried about Moody’s downgrade of the U.S. credit rating. But for the rest of us, it’s a big deal. 

The downgrade could make it more expensive to get a mortgage, car loan, or use your credit card, since the government might have to pay more to borrow money — and those costs can trickle down to everyone else.

title: Trump Signs Sweeping Online Harassment Bill into Law
description:
In a rare show of bipartisan unity, President Trump has signed the Take It Down Act — a sweeping law making it a federal crime to share nonconsensual intimate images, including AI-generated deepfakes, without the subject’s permission.

The law requires platforms to remove such content within 48 hours of a victim’s request, aiming to curb online sexual exploitation. While anti-harassment advocates call it a victory, digital rights groups warn the law could threaten free expression and privacy through overbroad censorship.

title: Public Broadcasting Is in Trouble Despite Sesame Street's Netflix Deal
description:
While Sesame Street’s move to Netflix is a major win for the iconic show, this solution is unique — it doesn’t address the broader crisis facing public broadcasting.

Many other PBS programs are still at risk of going off the air, following the Trump administration’s executive order to cut federal funding. This has already led to the loss of crucial grants like Ready to Learn. Without similar lifelines, countless educational children’s shows and resources that rely on public funding could face interruptions, delays, or cancellation — leaving families who depend on free, high-quality programming without vital support.

title: GOP Pushes Medicaid Cuts to Fund Billionaire Tax Breaks
description: The GOP doesn’t care that 13.7 million people will lose their insurance and 28,000 will die if Medicaid is cut. That’s not what this is about — they’re doing this to pay for tax cuts for billionaires.

title: Terror Strikes Fertility Clinic in Palm Springs
description:
A deadly explosion occurred outside the American Reproductive Centers fertility clinic in Palm Springs, California, on Saturday morning. The blast, believed to be caused by a car bomb, killed the suspected perpetrator and injured four others.

The FBI is investigating the incident as an act of terrorism, noting that the suspect had ties to anti-natalist and nihilistic ideologies.

This attack highlights the urgent need to protect reproductive rights and ensure access to fertility care. Clinics like ARC provide essential IVF and family-building services.

title: 177 Years to Freedom
description: ‘Are we in it for 177 years?’ Tynesha McHarris, co-founder of the Black Feminist Fund, reminds us that it took 177 years to end slavery from the first formal gathering to its abolition.

title: Abigail Disney Calls Out the Real Divide in America

title: Tesla Worker Killed in Safety Breach
description:
Victor Joe Gomez Sr., an electrician, was electrocuted and killed while inspecting electrical panels at Tesla’s Austin Gigafactory on August 1, 2024.

OSHA found Tesla responsible for serious safety violations — including failing to provide protective equipment and allowing work on live circuits. The resulting fine was just under $50,000, a trivial amount for Elon Musk and his multibillion-dollar company.

title: Tornadoes Devastate Kentucky and Missouri
description:
At least 27 people were killed when powerful tornadoes tore through Kentucky and Missouri on the night of May 16. The hardest-hit areas, including London and Somerset in Kentucky, saw entire neighborhoods flattened, vehicles tossed, and hundreds of homes destroyed.

While the exact cause of this tornado outbreak is still under investigation, scientists warn that the climate crisis is making severe weather events like these more frequent and intense — likely contributing to the conditions that fueled this deadly storm system.

title: Rep. Carpenter Confronts Immigration Policy Failures
description:
GA State Rep. Kasey Carpenter (R) has been outspoken in advocating for the release of Ximena Arias-Cristobal, a 19-year-old undocumented college student who was detained by ICE after a mistaken traffic stop in Dalton, GA.

Carpenter previously reassured his constituents that Trump’s immigration policy would not target law-abiding individuals, but Arias-Cristobal’s arrest and ongoing detention have called that assurance into question.

Carpenter has since acknowledged the lack of a viable pathway to citizenship for young people like Arias-Cristobal.

title: Cancer Registry for Firefighters Reinstated After DOGE Layoff Fallou
description:
Public outrage — including a speech from Rep. Hoyle — led to the reinstatement of the National Firefighter Registry for Cancer.

The registry was shut down in early April following GOP-led layoffs at the Department of Health and Human Services, which included the NIOSH staff responsible for the program and resulted in its indefinite suspension.

The registry is now back online to continue its critical work in understanding and reducing cancer risks among firefighters.

title: While Lawmakers Debate, Lives Hang in the Balance

As Washington lawmakers clash over Medicaid cuts, the real heartbreak is unfolding far from the halls of power — in states across the country.

For many, Medicaid isn’t just a program; it’s a lifeline. In North Carolina, for example, entire communities and hospitals depend on it.

The curriculum instructs students to analyze claims about ballot counting and mail-in voting that have been repeatedly debunked by independent fact-checkers and dismissed by every court that reviewed them.

title: From Misidentification to Deportation: Ximena’s Unjust Detention
description:
Ximena Arias-Cristobal, a 19-year-old undocumented college student, remains in ICE custody after Georgia police admitted she was mistakenly arrested during a traffic stop.

All charges were dropped when officials confirmed she was not the driver who committed the violation.

However, because Arias-Cristobal is in the U.S. without legal status, she was transferred to Whitfield County Jail, which has an agreement with ICE — allowing agents to detain ‘removable’ immigrants in ICE custody, where she now faces deportation.

title: From Tragedy to Action: How Nancy Davis Is Helping Others
description: In 2022, Nancy Davis was denied a medically necessary abortion in her home state of Louisiana. After going through that ordeal, she created the Nancy Davis Foundation so others wouldn’t have to face what she did. Thank you to the Brigid Alliance for sharing Nancy’s story.

title: SCOTUS Backs Trump Ban: Transgender Service Members Face Forced Exit
description:
The Supreme Court ruled that the Trump administration can enforce its ban on transgender individuals serving in the U.S. military.

Following the ruling, Hegseth issued a directive requiring all active-duty transgender troops to voluntarily separate from service by June 6. Those who do not leave voluntarily will face involuntary discharge.

Transgender troops forced out before serving 20 years will lose their pensions and retirement health care benefits.

Thank you to @thatoneguy_nick for sharing your story.

A woman was forced to show ID to prove her gender before being kicked out of a women’s bathroom at a Boston hotel, despite repeatedly asserting she is a woman — a stark example of why policing bathrooms is harmful and dehumanizing to LGBTQIA+ people.

In response, the hotel suspended the security guard involved, promised staff retraining on inclusive practices, and reaffirmed its commitment to being an inclusive space.

title: Trump’s Flower Tax Is Wilting Mother’s Day
description:
President Trump’s tariffs are hitting Americans right in the wallet just as people across the country get ready to honor mothers, caregivers, and loved ones.

In the weeks leading up to Mother’s Day, the U.S. imports more than $250 million worth of cut flowers — mostly from Colombia and Ecuador. Thanks to a new 10% tariff, those flowers now face a $25 million ‘flower tax,’ much of which gets passed on to Mother’s Day bouquets.

This policy doesn’t just mean higher prices for consumers — it also puts added pressure on over 11,000 local florist shops and small businesses that are already stretched thin.

title: Nobody Wants Elon’s Chrome Coffin on Wheels
description:
Aw, Elon can’t sell his ugly dumpster cars. Anyway…

About 10,000 Cybertrucks — the world’s most expensive box on wheels — are currently sitting at Elon Musk’s Tesla dealerships. Fewer people are buying them: In Q1 of this year, only 6,400 of these aluminum monstrosities were sold. Which is still 6,400 more than probably should have been, but here we are.

Between the car’s negative reputation (the Cybertruck has been nicknamed the ‘Swasticar’ after Musk’s not-so-subtle Nazi salute earlier this year and his blatant white supremacist beliefs) and a long list of recalls, it’s no surprise fewer people are lining up to make such an expensive mistake.

The Trump administration removed the ‘Faces of Gun Violence’ memorial from the headquarters of the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco, Firearms and Explosives (ATF).

title: Trump Ends Federal Funding for Public Media Putting Local Programs at Risk
description:
President Trump has signed an executive order to halt federal funding for NPR and PBS, citing claims of bias in their reporting.

While this move has sparked concerns about the future of beloved programs like ‘Sesame Street,’ the show itself is likely to remain financially stable.

The nonprofit behind ‘Sesame Street’ receives only a small portion of its funding from the federal government and relies mostly on distribution deals, royalties, and private donations.

However, many other educational and local programs — especially those serving rural areas — depend heavily on federal funds and could face severe cuts or even closure without this support.

title: What Happened to Pride at the Kennedy Center? Trump’s Appointees Did
description:
For weeks, LGBTQ+ events related to WorldPride and Pride Month started disappearing from the Kennedy Center’s calendar. And now, the Capital Pride Alliance has confirmed that the Tapestry of Pride programming planned for this June has either been moved or canceled. This comes after Trump appointed himself as the center’s chairman and replaced the board of trustees with Trump loyalists committed to his ‘anti-DEI’ agenda.

The Tapestry of Pride programming — including events like a family-friendly drag story time and a display of portions of the AIDS Memorial Quilt — will now be held at the WorldPride Welcome Center in D.C. Other events, like a performance from the Gay Men’s Chorus of Washington D.C., were also canceled.

The event, originally scheduled to start on May 17 and run through June 8, was expected to bring in millions of dollars in tourism revenue and visitors to our nation’s capital. Businesses have withdrawn their support from the event, including Eagle Canada, the country’s largest LGBTQ+ rights organization, and performers like Issa Rae have canceled their planned performances at the Kennedy Center in response.

title: Trump Admin Moves to Cut Lifeline for LGBTQ+ Youth in Crisis
description:
LGBTQ+ youth are four times more likely to attempt suicide. The Trump administration, under HHS Secretary Robert F. Kennedy, is slashing funding for a life-saving resource.

A leaked Health and Human Services budget revealed plans to eliminate services specifically for LGBTQ+ youth who call the national suicide hotline. Counselors trained with cultural competency to help those in crisis would no longer be available.

‘Here we are cutting off the nation’s lifeline to those in crisis,’ Paolo del Vecchio, former director of the Substance Abuse and Mental Health Administration’s Office of Recovery, told Mother Jones. ‘Due to the discriminatory practices of the Trump administration, they’re pulling that life preserver away from thousands and thousands of people.’

The leaked budget also revealed further cuts, including the elimination of the Head Start preschool program and reductions to the Centers for Disease Control.
